Reason_For_Change: V3.4: Test case updated to accommodate new ACIP Zoster recommendations. V2.0: New test case for version 2.0 which expanded scope into Adult recommendations
General_Description: This test case describes when a patient is administered a dose of ZVL (Zostavax) at age 60 years that the first dose of the RZV (Shingrix) vaccine should be forecasted.

Test_Case_Name: Zoster: Patient is overdue at 62 years of age for Zoster dose
Reason_For_Change: V3.4: Test case updated to accommodate new ACIP Zoster recommendations. V2.0: New test case for version 2.0 which expanded scope into Adult recommendations
General_Description: This test case describes when a patient is 62 years of age and has not been administered a Zoster vaccine that dose 1 (Shingrix) of the 2 dose series should be forecasted.

Test_Case_Name: Zoster: MMR to Zoster interval 28 days
Reason_For_Change: V3.4: Test case updated to accommodate new ACIP Zoster recommendations. V2.0: New test case for version 2.0 which expanded scope into Adult recommendations
General_Description: This test case describes when a patient is administered a Zoster (ZVL) vaccine dose 28 days after a MMR vaccine dose that the Zoster vaccine dose in considered valid. The engine should forecast dose #1 of the Zoster (Shingrix) vaccine.

Test_Case_Name: Zoster: MMR to Zoster interval 28 - 1 days
Forecast_Test_Type: Recommended based on minimum interval from live virus vaccine
Reason_For_Change: V3.4: Updated test case to reflect updated Zoster recommendations for Shingrix. V2.0: New test case for version 2.0 which expanded scope into Adult recommendations
General_Description: This test case describes when a patient is in early 50's and is administered a Zoster vaccine dose 28 -1 days after a MMR vaccine dose that the ZVL (Zostavax) vaccine dose is considered invalid. Zoster should be forecast in the future.

Test_Case_Name: Zoster: Patient has received dose 1 of the RZV (Shingrix) series
General_Description: This test case describes when a patient is administered dose #1 of the RZV vaccine that a second dose should be forecast.

Test_Case_Name: Zoster: Dose #2 of the RZV (Shringrix) vaccine administered at two months after dose #1
General_Description: This test case describes when a patient is administered dose #2 of the RZV vaccine at two months after dose #1 that the dose is considered to be valid.

Test_Case_Name: Zoster: Dose #2 (Shingrix) administered at 4 weeks after dose #1
General_Description: This test case describes when a patient is administered dose #2 of the RZV vaccine 4 weeks after the first dose that the series is considered complete.

Test_Case_Name: Zoster: Dose #2 of Shingrix administered at one year after dose #1
General_Description: This test case describes when a patient is administered the second dose of the Shingrix vaccine at one year later that the dose is considered to be valid. Series is complete.

Test_Case_Name: Zoster: Dose #2 (Shingrix) administered at 4 weeks - 1 days after dose #1
Forecast_Test_Type: Recommended based on minimum interval from invalid dose
Reason_For_Change: V3.5: Previous version was calculating the forecast from the first dose. This has been corrected to be from the previous dose (invalid dose #2). V4.0 Per email Dr Kroger the four day grace period can be used. Second dose has been changed to "valid".
General_Description: This test case describes that when a patient is administered the second dose of Shingrix vaccine at 4 weeks - 1 day that the dose is considered to be valid.

Test_Case_Name: Zoster: Patient is 50 with no previous history of Shringrix vaccine
General_Description: This test case describes when a patient is age 50 that dose 1 of the Shringrix vaccine should be forecasted.

Test_Case_Name: Zoster: Dose #1 of RZV administered 4 weeks after previous dose of ZVL
General_Description: This test case describes when a patient is administered the first dose of RZV (Shingrix) at 4 weeks after a previous dose of ZVL (Zostavax) that the dose is considered valid. Per current guidance RZV is recommended to be spaced 8 weeks after ZVL but it does not need to be repeated if administered at any point prior to that 8 weeks up to and including the same day.

Test_Case_Name: Zoster: ZVL and RZV (Shingrix) vaccine doses administered on the same day/time
General_Description: This test case describes when a patient receives a dose of ZVL (Shingrix)  and RZV (Zostavax) on the same day that the doses are considered to be valid.

Test_Case_Name: Zoster: Dose #1 of Shingrix 8 weeks after Dose #2 of Varicella vaccine
General_Description: This test case describes when a patient is administered a dose of Zoster (Shingrix) vaccine 8 weeks after the second dose of Varicella vaccine that the doses are considered to be valid.

Test_Case_Name: Zoster: Dose #1 of Shingrix 4 weeks after Dose #2 of Varicella vaccine
General_Description: This test case describes when dose #1 of the Shingrix vaccine is administered less than 8 weeks after the 2nd dose of the Varicella vaccine that the doses are considered to be valid.

Test_Case_Name: Zoster: Dose #1 of RZV administered 8 weeks after previous dose of ZVL
General_Description: This test case describes when a patient is administered the first dose of RZV 8 weeks after a previous dose of ZVL that the doses are valid.

Test_Case_Name: Zoster: Patient has received all three doses of the zoster vaccine
Reason_For_Change: v4.2: Added description
General_Description: This test case describes when a patient receives three (valid) doses of the Zoster vaccine that the series is considered Complete.

Test_Case_Name: Zoster: Dose #2 (Shingrix) administered at 4 weeks - 5 days after dose #1
Forecast_Test_Type: Recommended based on minimum interval from invalid dose
General_Description: This test case describes that when a patient is administered the second dose of Shingrix vaccine at less than 4 weeks - 4 days that the dose is considered not valid.

Test_Case_Name: Zoster: Dose #2 (Shingrix) administered at 4 weeks - 4 days after dose #1
Forecast_Test_Type: Recommended based on minimum interval from invalid dose
General_Description: This test case describes that when a patient is administered the second dose of Shingrix vaccine at 4 weeks - 4 day that the dose is considered to be valid.

Test_Case_Name: Zoster: Dose #1 of RZV administered 0 Days after previous dose of ZVL
General_Description: This test case describes when a patient is administered the first dose of RZV 0 days after a previous dose of ZVL that the doses are valid.
